				"string" : "### **C. The spread of influence**\n\n**Neighborhood function h(t)** ‚Üí **diffusion gradient**\nIn SOM, each input event updates not only the BMU but also its neighbors by a decaying function *h(distance, time)*.\nWard‚Äôs trails:\nupdates radiate outward, weakening with graph distance.\n\nThe Gaussian neighborhood = the canonical ‚Äútrail decay.‚Äù\n\n### **D. Distributed coherence**\n\n**SOM learning rate & radius decay** ‚Üí **FolkMemory dampening**\nWard‚Äôs system stabilizes because trails grow *weaker* as they propagate.\nSOM:\nboth Œ∑(t) and radius(t) shrink.\nLess turbulence ‚Üí convergence on a stable memory topology.\n\n### **E. Spatial substrate**\n\n**SOM grid** ‚Üí **FolkMemory‚Äôs logical neighborhood graph**\nWard‚Äôs objects form adjacency relationships (servers, shards, authority trails).\nKohonen‚Äôs grid is a fixed adjacency graph with lateral inhibition + neighborhood excitation (SOM 2001, Sec. 4.2) .\n\n### **F. Knowledge emergence**\n\n**SOM‚Äôs ordered map** ‚Üí **FolkMemory‚Äôs emergent shared memory**\nJohn Day‚Äôs ‚Äúfundamental invariant‚Äù pattern applies directly:\ncomplex systems converge when local recursive updates enforce consistent behavior across neighbors‚Äîno central controller.\n\nSOM ordering is exactly such an invariant.\n"
