				"string" : "# üü¶ STAGE 9.3 ‚Äî GT Curriculum Ladder (Extended)\n\nThis is the version ready to drop into our ‚ÄúCurriculum Ladder‚Äù page.\n\n## **Stage 9.3.1 ‚Äî From Numbers to Distributed Objects**\n\n1. Start with a heatmap of all reference vectors in 2D/3D numeric space.\n2. Then show the *same objects* as interactive cards in a ‚Äúdistributed view‚Äù:\n\n   * nodes as neurons,\n   * edges as neighborhood relations,\n   * color = activation\n   * size = influence weight h.\n\nStudents now ‚Äúsee‚Äù Kohonen‚Äôs grid as a distributed system.\n\n## **Stage 9.3.2 ‚Äî Show a Single Step as a FolkMemory Event**\n\nAnimation of:\n\n1. Input arrives (highlight vector).\n2. BMU lights up (‚Äúpromotion‚Äù).\n3. Neighborhood nodes glow by decreasing intensity (‚Äútrail‚Äù).\n4. Weight updates ripple outward.\n\n**This is the ‚Äúdiffusion trail.‚Äù**\n\n## **Stage 9.3.3 ‚Äî Connect to Day‚Äôs Model of Networks**\n\nShow that SOM‚Äôs update rule enforces:\n\n* local consistency,\n* global invariants,\n* stability by decreasing learning rate,\n* robustness against noise.\n\nExactly Day‚Äôs description of correct recursive distributed protocols.\n\n## **Stage 9.3.4 ‚Äî Introduce Shards**\n\nAdd optional metadata to each neuron (e.g., a ‚Äústory,‚Äù provenance, or snippet) to stress that:\n\n* Reference vectors need not be numeric-only.\n* They can be small objects with state (FolkMemory object).\n\n## **Stage 9.3.5 ‚Äî Show Emergence**\n\nUse a time-lapse visualization:\n\n* early chaos ‚Üí\n* neighborhoods forming ‚Üí\n* stable topological order.\n\nExplain:\n‚ÄúThis is what happens when distributed objects share experience through trails.‚Äù\n\n## **Stage 9.3.6 ‚Äî Interpret Ordering as Knowledge Consolidation**\n\nWard Cunningham:\n‚ÄúThe authority trails keep history alive as new shards align.‚Äù\n\nKohonen:\n‚ÄúReference vectors converge on centroids representing data manifold topology.‚Äù \n"
